---
import LightLayout from '../../../layouts/LightLayout.astro';
---

<LightLayout title="Script · WhatsApp" description="Structured script by blocks for Stripe Product Sense.">

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-12 pb-6">
    <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Back to hub</a>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mt-6 mb-4">
      <span class="text-5xl">💬</span>
      <div>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black !my-0" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">Script · WhatsApp</h1>
        <p class="!my-1 font-medium" style="color: var(--color-primary);">~6 min · universal product, granular sub-segmentation</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16">
    <div class="prose-factory">

      <div class="card !p-5 my-6" style="background: rgba(236,72,153,0.10); border: 1px solid rgba(236,72,153,0.25);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">📌 How to use this script</h3>
        <p class="!mb-0">WhatsApp is a universal product: you'll be asked to segment well or fall into the obvious. The strong piece is <strong>"the closed circle of trust"</strong> as differentiator vs open social networks. And the transplant to over-70s is very likely to come up.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[USER]</h2>
      <p>"I'm going to talk about <strong>WhatsApp</strong>, which I use every day. My primary user is not 'people who send messages', because that covers 2 billion people. <strong>My primary user is the adult aged 25 to 45 with a communication network that is primarily family and professional</strong>, not openly social."</p>
      <p>"I choose this segment because it's where WhatsApp has the strongest retention and where a product change has the most leverage. I'll touch on other segments as contrast: teenagers who use Instagram DMs more, over-70s who mostly use voice calls, microbusiness owners who use WhatsApp Business."</p>

      <h2>[SUB-SEGMENTS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>The family communicator.</strong> Groups with parents, kids, cousins. Daily messages, photos of children, long voice notes. Lives in active group chats."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The professional communicator.</strong> Mixes work and personal in the same app. 1-to-1 chats, shared documents, voice notes to coordinate meetings. Needs to be able to distinguish personal from work."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The casual consumer.</strong> Uses WhatsApp to confirm plans, not to converse. Cares about stories only from close people, ignores channels and catalogues."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"I'm going to focus on <strong>the family communicator</strong>, because it's the sub-segment that most defines WhatsApp's moat: the network is made up of real close people, not followers."</p>

      <h2>[ECOSYSTEM]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Personal messaging</strong>, competing with iMessage in the US, Telegram in Eastern Europe, Signal among the privacy-conscious, Line in Japan, KakaoTalk in Korea."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Closed social network</strong>, where WhatsApp is very different from Instagram, Twitter, TikTok. <strong>The closed circle of trust is the ontological difference</strong>: on WhatsApp you don't add people you don't know, there's no algorithm pushing content at you, and that turns the app into a qualitatively distinct space from open social networks."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Business communication layer</strong>, where WhatsApp Business competes with SMS, email, customer service tools, and increasingly with conversational AI interfaces."</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 "Closed circle of trust" is your anchor sentence. Memorise it. It separates you from the candidate who says "WhatsApp is like Instagram without stories".</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[PROPOSAL]</h2>
      <p>"For the family communicator, I propose <strong>personal tags in group chats to organise conversations by sub-topics</strong>. In a family group of 15 people, conversations get mixed (birthday plans, baby photos, doctor recommendations, politics). My proposal: any member can tag a message with a topic, and all messages with that tag form a sub-thread within the group, without fragmenting the main conversation."</p>
      <p>"It connects to the sub-segment because it solves the number-one problem of the large family group: lost context. And it respects the closed-circle principle: it doesn't add people, it organises the conversation that already exists."</p>

      <h2>[EDGE CASES]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, tag abuse. If everyone tags everything, the system becomes noise. Mitigation: tags are suggested by context (AI detects topic), not freely created."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, privacy within the group. Some conversations are sensitive (doctor recommendations, personal problems). Solution: tags are not public by default; each user sees only their own or those explicitly shared."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, group fragmentation. If sub-threads become too active, the main conversation dies. Solution: tags don't split the group, they enrich it; tagged messages also appear in the main feed."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[RISKS: TIGER + PAPER TIGER]</h2>
      <p>"<strong>🐅 Tiger:</strong> degradation of simplicity. WhatsApp wins because it's simple. Adding tags, sub-threads, organisational layers is exactly what killed Slack for casual use. Mitigation: the feature is hidden by default and activates by usage, not by configuration."</p>
      <p>"<strong>📰 Paper Tiger:</strong> 'Telegram already has topics in groups, WhatsApp is late'. Looks real but isn't. Telegram topics are heavy, require an admin, fragment the group. My proposal is lighter and respects the continuous-flow principle. And WhatsApp's user base doesn't move for marginal features, it moves based on where their contacts are. Arriving late to a feature isn't a problem when you own the network."</p>

      <h2>[METRICS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Target:</strong> messages read per user in large groups (10+ members). Measures whether organisation improves engagement."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Leading:</strong> tag adoption rate by active member in large group in first 30 days. Target 25%."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Lagging:</strong> group retention at 6 months (% of created groups still active). Target +3pp."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Guard rail:</strong> average time in app per session. Cannot rise more than 5%. If it does, we've created friction instead of clarity."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[TRANSPLANT]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'OK, now do it for users over 70'."</p>
      <p>"<strong>OK, let me pause. The context changes.</strong>"</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, I assumed native digital familiarity. For over-70s that's not safe to assume. Many learned late, the learning curve for new features is steep."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, I assumed autonomous use. For over-70s often there's a family member helping, and that changes the UX flow. We have to design 'for two people using one device'."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, I assumed a need for organisation. The over-70 user often has fewer groups, less message volume. A tagging feature doesn't solve a problem they actually have."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"With those assumptions broken, my proposal transforms. Instead of tags, I'd propose <strong>an assisted reading mode</strong>: voice notes with automatic transcription and option to enlarge text significantly, messages read aloud on demand, and clear identification of who sent each message (large photo + prominent name, not a small avatar). The over-70 user's problem isn't organisation, it's comprehension and accessibility."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 9 executed: the transplant is not the same feature with bigger text, it's a different product for a different problem.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[IF THEY PUSH BACK]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'tags create extra work for the user. Why not use AI to auto-organise?'"</p>
      <p>"Good question. Let me distinguish two things. <strong>Automatic organisation</strong>, where the AI decides what is what, is problematic in personal messaging because the user loses control over how their own content is categorised, and in family chats that's very sensitive (a politically charged message mis-tagged can generate conflict). <strong>Assisted organisation</strong>, where the AI suggests and the user confirms, keeps the user's authority over their own content. My proposal lives in the second mode. The difference is one of mental model: the app is an assistant, not a curator."</p>

      <hr class="my-10" />

      <div class="card !p-6 my-8" style="background: var(--color-primary-soft);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">🎯 The three anchor sentences</h3>
        <ol class="!mb-0">
          <li><strong>"The closed circle of trust is the ontological difference"</strong> (situating WhatsApp).</li>
          <li><strong>"The network doesn't move for features, it moves based on where the contacts are"</strong> (Paper Tiger against Telegram).</li>
          <li><strong>"Assisted organisation, not automatic organisation"</strong> (the finer distinction).</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-3 mt-10">
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/github" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← GitHub</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Hub</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/claude-code" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Claude Code →</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</LightLayout>
